sec.p:
Species delimitation is difficult for inquilines based on morphology. For example, 

Synergus japonicus

and 

S. gifuensis

Ashmead, 1904 were treated as two different forms of 

Synergus japonicus

based on similarity in morphology, but are distinct in life cycles and impact on the gall structures (

; 

; 

; 

). DNA barcoding as a complementary taxonomic approach has considerable utility for inquilines and the status of some Western Palaearctic 

Synergus

species has been questioned based on disagreement between morphospecies and MOTUs (

). In this study, the ASAP method was used in support of the new species, 

Synergus dilatatus

sp. nov., with an integrative approach combining morphological and molecular data, and the results were consistent.
